remixed_from.title: Kossel magnetic z-probe mount with zero X-Y offset to avoid effector tilt problems/errors. Tested 100%.

title: Kossel magnetic endstop z-probe (zero x/y & low z offset)

description.text:
Based on paul_delta's zero x/y offset probe (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1198256), with which I had the very first real success calibrating my Delta printer using this online calculator: http://escher3d.com/pages/wizards/wizarddelta.php by the user dc42. Compared to paul_delta's design, this remix has some benefits:
  • Lower z offset (paul_delta's design: ~ 120 mm, this design ~ 30 mm)
  • Less mass -> less tendency to swing/vibrate due to high acceleration
  • Low activation height (~ 0.5 mm)
    • As with paul_delta's design you will need some rare-earth magnets, which are glued onto the z-probe and the effector (see photos). I used 10 mm diameter and 1 mm thick ones. If you want to use others - just adapt the .scad file. Also, if you have other Delta effector offset etc, see the .scad. Using this probe, David's calculator and Repetier's bed correction, I managed to lower the bed height deviation to +/- 50 µm max (25 µm standard dev.). Remarks:
  • I had slightly better results (standard deviation from 31 µm down to 25 µm) when not neglecting the residual x/y offset (for me x = -1 mm, y = -1,3 mm). But your mileage may vary. To measure it I use following method:
    1. Position the nozzle ~ 0.2 mm above bed (x/y = 0), extrude 1 mm filament and move the nozzle up. There should a little blob be sticking on the bed surface now.
    2. Attach probe, move nail exactly above the extruded piece on the bed. Your offsets are the negated x/y values you can read off your display / host software.
  • This probe will fit paul_delta's probe storage. :)
  • I do recommend a probing speed of 2 mm/s - ish for most accurate results.
  • This was my very first experience with OpenSCAD. I LOVE IT!
  • V1 is the old design with a nail (see updates below). I would recommend to use V2. V2 has a non-rotating pin, which should be printed in ABS, see printing / post-printing.
    • Update 17.02.2016:
  • Added video of the endstop in action.
  • There will be a V2 coming soon! I have the slightest deviation in z-height (~ 50 µm) when the nail is rotating in it's guide hole. I am trying to print out the probe point in ABS and make it non-rotating.
    • Update 18.02.2016:
  • V2 is online and works like a charm! :) Non-rotating probe pin included.
    • Update 03.03.2016:
  • Just to let you guys know: I upped to 2mm thick magnets, as they are much beefier and hold the probe in place very securely. I like that much more compared to 1 mm thick ones.
    • Update 18.05.2016:
  • Added V3 of the z probe with additional headroom around the probe pin (before, there was a chance the z probe body would hit bed clamps or similar). Also added a version without the pin, if you guys like that more. I personally slightly prefer the pin, as it gives a defined probing location.
    Pls watch out: The .stl's of V3 are made to fit this thing: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1540203
    So if you want to use V3 for your standard Kossel setup, pls adapt .scad to "magnetsep = 22;"

Printer:

Folger Tech. Kossel 2020 Rev.B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm .. 0.3 mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

  • Probe: Use thick perimeter/shell/top/bottom (> 1 mm), so that the frame is stable. Print either in ABS or PLA.

  • Pin: Do print in ABS at a rather slow setting (10 sec per layer minimum). ABS is needed, as this pin will contact the heated bed. PLA will likely become to soft (did not test though... :) ).

• After printing, tap the M3 screw holes, which hold the endstop in place. If you dont have a tapper, try to use a screw (I did not test this).
  • The probe pin will likely not print perfectly. Flatten the pin to a reasonable level (sandpaper works very well) and give it a little bevel.
  • Put the probe pin into place (flat side towards frame).
  • Put the endstop + 2 M3x12 (or 16 or 8) into place and tighten the screws. If needed, secure the endstop with a bit of superglue.
  • Super-glue the two magnets onto the probe.
  • When the glue is dry, put the other two magnets on top of the probe magnets. Put a drop of super-glue on top of those. Position the probe under the effector and push hard. The magnets should stick well to the effector after ~ 30 seconds. Watch out to A) not glue the supermagnets together and B) not put superglue residue on top of the magnet's surface.
    • And finally 7: G33, G30, G29 or whatever your firmware needs. :) Have fun!

Thank you

  • David, for his ingenious calculator. http://www.thingiverse.com/dc42/about

comments.text: How does this work? And will it work on the 1.5?
comments.author: dan3008

comments.text:
The counterbore washer will work on the v1.5 but the other part won't.
The x axis carriage collides with the head of the bolt which holds the bearing at the end opposite the stepper motor. Replace the existing part with the counterbored washer and swap the bolt for a shorter one (the v1.0 chassis corner bolts work) to prevent it from touching the PCB. Then you can tweak the firmware to allow 90mm of travel in the x axis.
It was someone else on rc groups . com who worked it out by drilling his printer. I just didn't fancy risking that on mine so designed and printed replacement parts.

After making Thing-O-Fun's functional differential gear system and playing with it for a while I realized that this thing just had to be motorized. I had a Solarbotics GM9 gear motor lying around and it was a perfect fit. All that was needed was a modified input shaft to match up with the shaft on the gear motor and a base to hold the batteries and power switch. I included the scad file so that you can easily change the switch opening to fit your switch. Watch it in motion at http://youtu.be/bFceF0CeGFk

• Make the functional differential gear system (you can skip the shaft and one of the handles, as they are not needed with the motorized version.
  • Print the base and the input shaft.
  • Put the Input Shaft on the Input Pinion and assemble the gear system.
  • Line up the GM9 shaft with the Input Shaft and hole it in place.
  • Solder wires ~3 inches long onto the GM9 terminals.
  • Drill two holes about 2.8mm into the stand, using the holes in the GM9 body as a guide. Use the M3x22 screws to mount the motor.
  • Solvent weld the gear system to the base.
  • Glue in the battery holder, install the switch, and hook it all up.

description.text: I couldn't find a usb charger that takes AA batteries with >1A power so I made one yesterday using a spare cable, some solder, and a couple 3d-printed parts I whipped up. Use 4 batteries if they are 1.2V and 3 if they are 1.5V - and wire them in series (google it if you don't know how).   • Print the appropriately-sized battery holder using a customized http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:128069
    --OR-- Use the included 4xAA battery holder and simply short one of the battery slots if you are using 3xAA 1.5V batteries
    (2.5 double check that the dimensions will fit your USB female tip, adjust as necessary)
  • Print the case + sliding top. I used 1 shell + 8% infill. While you wait:
  • Wire up the battery holder as shown. I used solder.
  • Cut up a female USB cable end, short the data lines (green and white, usually) and connect the red and black to battery holder
  • Hot glue // adhere the USB female tip into the holder

title: Deck holders: Firefly the Board Game

description.text:
While there are several great deck holders available, unfortunately they didn't work so great for the cards when they had a card slip over them. I also wanted to practice with Fusion 360, so I made this design. Considering that this is my third design, I think it came out pretty decent.
I still have a lot to learn, so I welcome some suggestions for improvements. Note: I am using the Robo R1 +, unfortunately they don't have that option yet. Update 2/12/2016: I have uploaded three versions of the card holder.
Version one is basically my original design. It takes a bit more time and filament than the other two designs, but is fairly certain to print nicely. It also should require no supports. Version 2 has the sides thinned out to cut back on filament and time printing. It only offers a minor improvement for both over version 1. No supports should be needed, though the side parts can wobble a bit during printing. Version 3 is the most efficient as far as filament and time, but may print best with some supports. I have included a Fusion 3D export file, just let me know if you need some other file format. I would also welcome some input on which design works the best. Thank you, and have a great day. :-)

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.3

Infill:

100

Notes: I printed the first version with the fast settings, simply to see if it really would really not require any supports. It seems to do perfectly fine. My second attempt printing it was on medium settings, in order to see if there were any improvements in quality. All considered, the increase in quality really didn't do much for it. I tried to optimize the design for using less filament, so changing the infill will only save a small amount of filament and time, it isn't really worth it. It took about 3 hours for me, with the fast settings. It isn't amazing, but it is not horrible either. I will see if I can find ways to shave the time down more. Just a side note, I print it with the back end facing up. I am still getting used to alignment in Fusion, so the models are kinda oddly placed. Feel free to ask me for clarification on anything.

Expanding my digitally fabricated jewelry collection, I decided to create a pair of lightning bolt earrings for my first project using the Makerbot. I designed these electrifying earrings using Autodesk Inventor software and extruded the sketch by .1". The lightning bolt measures roughly 2-1/4" long.
